# Spec 013 — Commute Depth 2: Departure Ranges, Travel Modes, Feedback

Status: Draft
Owner: <you>
Related: 011-commute-accuracy (supersedes its R2 single-sample and R5
two-call numbers), 003-commute-depth (band machinery), 004 (hardening reused)

## Overview

Three upgrades to how commutes are estimated and experienced. First, drive
estimates sample the rush window (three departures per direction) and report
an honest **range** — "Drive home: 55–73 min" — instead of one typical-point
number. Second, a travel-mode switcher adds **walking and cycling** (same
Mapbox APIs, different profile; public transit is explicitly out of scope —
Mapbox has no transit product, and real transit means a new provider or
self-hosted OpenTripPlanner, deferred to a future spec). Third, the UI
finally *shows* when commute data is in flight, and a recenter button brings
the map back to the work pin.

## Requirements

- **R1 — Departure-window sampling (drive).** Drive-mode `/api/commute`
  samples three departures per leg (AM home→work 7:15/8:00/8:45; PM
  work→home 4:30/5:15/6:00 origin-local, next weekday) and returns per-leg
  min/max minutes plus the window labels. An uncached drive pair reserves
  **6** budget calls (supersedes 011 R5's 2). A leg is valid when ≥1 sample
  succeeds; the pair is a 404 (cached) when either leg has no valid sample.
- **R2 — Travel modes.** `mode=drive|walk|cycle` on both `/api/isochrone`
  and `/api/commute` (default drive, invalid → 422). Walk/cycle use the
  `walking`/`cycling` profiles with no `depart_at` (durations are
  time-invariant): isochrone fetches ONE contour (no traffic bands, no
  variation summary, reserves 1), commute fetches one call per direction
  (reserves 2) returning min==max and null windows. Cache keys include mode.
- **R3 — Loading feedback.** While a commute estimate is in flight the
  detail panel shows a muted "Estimating commute…" line; while the reach
  overlay is refetching (pin drag, mode/minutes change) a small map chip
  shows "Updating reach…". Both disappear on settle; failures stay silent
  per 011 R6.
- **R4 — Recenter on pin.** A floating, keyboard-accessible map button
  (≥40 px) flies the map back to the work pin, reusing the existing
  recenter flow.
- **R5 — Mode in shared URLs.** `tmode=walk|cycle` round-trips through the
  query string (omitted for the drive default), composing with 009 R5.
- **R6 — Wire-format break is contained.** `CommuteEstimate` is restructured
  (mode + per-leg min/max/window fields). The only consumer is this repo's
  own frontend, deployed atomically with the backend; in-process caches
  reset on deploy. No external-compat shim.

## Non-functional / Constraints

- All 004 hardening unchanged: rate limit, geofence, snapping, daily budget,
  24 h caches. Worst-case daily uncached drive pairs drop 3× (6 calls vs 2)
  — still ample under `MAPBOX_DAILY_CALL_BUDGET=2000` and the 100k/month
  free tier.
- Six sequential upstream calls ≈ ~2 s worst-typical — acceptable for a
  debounced, now-visibly-loading best-effort line.
- Mapbox's 60-minute isochrone cap applies to all profiles.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Drive mode: panel shows "Drive to work: A–B min" / "Drive home: C–D
      min" with departure windows named; logs show 6 upstream calls per
      fresh pair; re-selection spends 0.
- [ ] Walk mode: single contour on the map (no scenario bands or fold),
      "Walk to work: ~N min" with no window; 2 upstream calls per fresh
      pair, 1 per fresh isochrone.
- [ ] "Estimating commute…" appears immediately on selection and resolves;
      "Updating reach…" appears during pin drags; neither lingers.
- [ ] The recenter button flies back to the pin from anywhere; reachable by
      keyboard with a visible focus ring.
- [ ] `?tmode=walk` deep link opens in walk mode; drive URLs stay clean.
- [ ] `pytest` and `npm run test` green across the new sampling, mode,
      loading, and URL tests.

## Out of Scope (explicit)

- **Public transit** (no Mapbox product; future spec would weigh TravelTime/
  Google-class providers — new billing + key handling — against self-hosted
  OpenTripPlanner + GTFS infrastructure).
- Pessimistic/percentile traffic (unchanged from 011); user-chosen departure
  times; parallelized upstream fan-out (revisit only if latency feels bad).

